            </p>

            <div class="checklist">
                <h3>Things to Look For:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Loose Outlets:</strong> Tighten any loose outlets as
                        needed.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Cover Plates:</strong> Make sure all outlets have cover
                        plates in good condition.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="blog-section">
            <h2>2. INSPECT THE ELECTRICAL PANEL</h2>
            <p>
                Your panel should be clearly labeled, organized, and free from any
                visible defects.
            </p>

            <div class="checklist">
                <h3>Inspection Checklist:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Proper Labeling:</strong> Ensure each circuit is clearly
                        labeled for easy identification.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>No Overcrowded Circuits:</strong> Avoid overloading any
                        individual circuit with too many devices.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="blog-section">
            <h2>3. TEST ALL GFCI OUTLETS</h2>
            <p>
                All Ground Fault Circuit Interrupter outlets are required in certain
                areas like bathrooms and kitchens.
            </p>

            <div class="checklist">
                <h3>Prevention Tips:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Test Monthly:</strong> Use the test button to ensure
                        each GFCI outlet is functioning correctly.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Replace Faulty GFCIs:</strong> Replace non-functioning
                        or outdated GFCI outlets.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="blog-section">
            <h2>4. CLEAR ACCESS TO ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS</h2>
            <p>
                Make sure there is easy access to your electrical panel, outlets,
                and other components.
            </p>

            <div class="checklist">
                <h3>Key Priorities:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Adequate Access:</strong> Keep min. 3 feet clear space
                        in front of your panels.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Remove Obstructions:</strong> Clear away any items
                        blocking access to your wiring.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="blog-section">
